<br>
Better example would be if you train every day for a marathon.  Completing the marathon in a fast enough time qualifies you to enter the olympics.<br>
<br>
You beat the marathon, and are awarded a trophy, and are allowed to be an Olympic competitor in the coming summer.<br>
<br>
You give the trophy to your friend, and he licks it, and now the olympic committee says he can be an olympic competitor too.<br>
<br>
And then that friend hands the trophy to someone else, who licks it, and suddenly they're in the olympics as well.<br>
<br>
Anyone who tells you there isn't an underlying level of competition going on between the high end guilds is lying to you.  And taking advantage of a no-drop key to gain access for large portions of a guild to a zone when only a small portion of the guild actually earned the access is essentially cheating (from a competetive standpoint).<br>
<br>
It's akin to qualifying for wimbledon, only to discover that half the people you're competing against didn't qualify, they just bribed the judges.  It's a whole different situation than &quot;taking away form your earlier accomplishments&quot;, etc.<br>
<br>
